Current solar-EV setups are essentially three separate boxes: [eqmagpro](https://www.eqmagpro.com/india-launches-first-solar-powered-ev-charging-station-with-second-life-batteries-eq/)
- Solar inverter (DC→AC)
- AC charger or DC charger fed by AC grid
- Optional battery system with its own inverter

This means **multiple conversion stages**, each with 3–8% losses, and no intelligent DC-coupling. The Bengaluru RE2EV pilot with second-life batteries is innovative but still uses conventional AC-coupled architecture. [ampernext](https://www.ampernext.com/products/first-30kw-dc-dc-solar-ev-charger/)

